<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/jeito-capital-1-2b/" data-wpel-link="internal">Jeito Capital Raises $1.2B to Drive European Biopharma Growth</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Record Fundraising for European Biopharma</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Jeito Capital, based in Paris, just pulled in $1.2 billion for its second fund, Jeito II — which actually topped their expected goal. That’s a huge milestone, making it the biggest raise so far by any independent European fund that’s focused on biopharma. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Jeito’s first fund wrapped up in 2021 with $630 million. Since then, their assets under management have tripled, hitting €1.6 billion in five years. The way Jeito works is pretty focused: they back about 15 to 20 companies that are already in clinical stages, and they can put as much as €150 million into each one. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This is a sharp break from those “spray-and-pray” tactics you see with most early-stage investors. What makes Jeito stand out is how focused they are. They don’t just invest anywhere—they look for companies chasing real breakthroughs in tough diseases. We’re talking cancer, obesity, neurological and autoimmune disorders, reproductive medicine, heart disease—big stuff.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">But honestly, Jeito isn’t just handing out money and walking away. They roll up their sleeves. Their team jumps right in alongside these companies, sharing hard-won experience in drug development, regulations, manufacturing, and distribution. That kind of hands-on approach helps these treatments make it through clinical trials and reach patients faster.</span></p>
<h2><b>Strategic Investment Approach</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Dr. Rafaèle Tordjman, both a physician and a scientist, founded Jeito. Her approach is pretty focused—she prefers to make meaningful, patient-centered investments instead of scattering money around lots of early-stage startups. It’s a response to a big problem in European biotech, where companies in the clinical stage often struggle to find steady funding for critical Phase 2 and 3 trials.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">According to Tordjman, the latest fund demonstrates confidence in Europe’s biopharma ecosystem. “This strong signal shows that European companies can drive major therapeutic innovation and economic benefit when provided with financial and strategic resources,” she said.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Jeito’s portfolio already shows signs of success. In July 2024, Merck acquired EyeBio for up to $3 billion, while Biogen purchased HI-Bio for up to $1.8 billion. Together, these two deals generated nearly $5 billion for Jeito-backed companies in a single month.</span></p>
<h2><b>Concentrated European Focus</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Unlike other investors such as Sofinnova Partners or Novo Holdings, Jeito focuses on mid- to late-stage clinical companies and invests primarily in Europe. The firm selects businesses that are poised to benefit from significant capital and expertise to reach advanced clinical stages and market launch.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Jeito II plans to back about 15 to 20 companies, putting in up to €150 million for each one. By investing big, Jeito helps these companies speed up development, cut down on financial risks, and move smoothly through key clinical trials.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">But Jeito doesn&#8217;t just throw money at them and walk away. Smaller biotech firms usually struggle to hire people for tough jobs in regulatory affairs, manufacturing, or commercial operations. Jeito steps in with its own experts to guide them through all that complexity. Thanks to this hands-on support, more promising therapies actually make it to patients and into the market.</span></p>
<h2><b>Current Portfolio and Future Outlook<br />
</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_199713" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-199713" class="size-full wp-image-199713" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/a-futuristic-poster-showcases-a-vibrant-_N5QFsp1JTbexmibWZNP6_A_HivNgv-DQaSaBdMD2J6Ngg.png" alt="European biopharma investments expanding across multiple therapeutic areas with strong funding and innovation growth." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-199713" class="wp-caption-text">Jeito strengthens Europe’s biotech ecosystem by backing clinical-stage companies and driving innovation across major disease areas. Source: Created by Ventureburn</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Jeito II has already invested in companies targeting obesity, oncology, neurology, autoimmune diseases, and </span><a href="https://southdenver.com/what-is-cardiometabolic-disease/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">cardiometabolic conditions</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">. One notable investment is Alveus Therapeutics, which raised $197 million in February 2026 for next-generation obesity treatments, with Jeito as the lead investor.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The firm’s previous fund also generated three significant exits, including EyeBio and HI-Bio. These successes highlight the potential of Jeito’s concentrated investment strategy and its focus on European clinical-stage companies.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Concerns remain about Europe’s ability to scale and retain its life sciences innovation. Despite strong scientific foundations, most EU-based biotech companies go public outside Europe. Jeito’s approach aims to reverse this trend by providing long-term funding and operational support for European ventures.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Jeito is right in step with where the industry’s headed. Big pharma’s hold on those blockbuster drugs is slipping thanks to patent expirations, and people are predicting about a $400 billion revenue hit by 2033. So, these companies are out there hunting for the next big breakthrough, mostly by grabbing up new therapies with potential. Jeito is betting on clinical-stage companies, aiming to cash in when buyouts or major partnerships happen.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: <a href="https://ventureburn.com/sidewinder-therapeutics-137m/" data-wpel-link="internal">Sidewinder Therapeutics Raises $137 Million to Advance Bispecific ADCs</a></span></p>
<h2><b>Strengthening Europe’s Biopharma Ecosystem</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The fund’s size also allows Jeito to influence the wider European biotech ecosystem. The firm aims to demonstrate that European companies can lead in therapeutic innovation and generate significant economic value.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Tordjman said the fund’s closing was a milestone for the sector. “Jeito II validates a patient-driven investment strategy that accelerates clinical development and unlocks commercial potential,” she explained. The firm plans to maintain a hands-on approach across its portfolio, combining capital with operational guidance.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Jeito II’s concentrated strategy offers several advantages.This approach gives companies the money they need to run advanced clinical programs, so they don’t have to keep chasing after small rounds of funding. That takes a lot of pressure off and bumps up their chances of pulling off both clinical and commercial wins. It’s also good news for Europe’s biotech scene as a whole.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Jeito really stands out from the crowd of European investors. Instead of spreading itself thin, the firm zeroes in on mid- to late-stage companies and actually rolls up its sleeves to offer operational help. That way, Jeito fills the funding and know-how gaps that usually hold back clinical-stage biopharma companies in Europe.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To stay updated on crypto venture capital funding and market trends, visit our </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/category/news/venture-capital/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">venture capital news section</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> for more insights.</span></p>
