					<description><![CDATA[<p>Advancing Next-Generation ADCs Sidewinder Therapeutics, a biotech outfit out of San Diego, just blew past expectations with their latest Series B round. They pulled in $137 million—more than anyone guessed.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/sidewinder-therapeutics-137m/" data-wpel-link="internal">Sidewinder Therapeutics Raises $137 Million to Advance Bispecific ADCs</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Advancing Next-Generation ADCs</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Sidewinder Therapeutics, a biotech outfit out of San Diego, just blew past expectations with their latest Series B round. They pulled in $137 million—more than anyone guessed. Frazier Life Sciences and Novartis Venture Fund led the charge, but they weren’t alone. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Some big names joined in: OrbiMed, DCVC Bio, Goldman Sachs Alternatives’ Life Sciences team, Samsara BioCapital, Longwood Fund, Astellas Venture Management, and Alexandria Venture Investments all threw their weight behind it.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">All together, Sidewinder has racked up $162 million to date. That’s no small feat. And with this fresh funding, they’ve added a few new faces to their board: Daniel Estes from Frazier, Michal Silverberg from Novartis, Josh Richardson from Goldman Sachs, and John Hamer from DCVC Bio.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">So, what’s all the excitement about? Sidewinder’s building next-gen bispecific antibody-drug conjugates—ADCs for short. But these aren’t just the usual cancer therapies you’ve seen before. Sidewinder’s ADCs are designed to target receptor co-complexes. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Those are clusters you usually find hanging out in certain solid tumors, not in healthy tissue. The whole idea is that their drugs home in on these clusters, slip straight into the cancer cells, drop the therapy right where it’s needed, and leave the healthy cells untouched.</span></p>
<h2><b>Focused Pipeline and Clinical Plans</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Sidewinder is all about tackling cancers that don’t have much going for them. They’re focusing on squamous cell carcinomas in the lung, head, and neck, and some hard-hitting GI cancers like </span><a href="https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/colorectal-cancer" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">colorectal cancer</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">. What’s different is their way of targeting cancer cells directly, which makes treatments safer and lets patients avoid a bunch of nasty side effects.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Eric Murphy, who runs the show as CEO and Co-Founder, says this Series B financing just shows investors really believe in what Sidewinder’s doing. He explained that technological breakthroughs are enabling next-generation bispecific ADCs. “Sidewinder is eager to lead this wave of innovation and advance promising therapies for patients with cancer,” he said.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The firm plans to advance its lead program into clinical development in 2027. Internal discovery efforts have produced antibody sequences engineered to target receptor co-complexes consisting of an oncogenic driver and an internalising receptor. This design enhances specificity and ensures efficient drug delivery to tumour cells.</span></p>
<h2><b>Strategic Partnerships and Platform Technologies</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Sidewinder’s joining forces with Lonza to tap into Synaffix’s site-specific linker-payload tech for a bunch of new projects. They can attach drug payloads directly to antibodies, so the treatment goes straight to its target and packs a punch. That means the drugs do their job better and you don’t get hit with as many side effects.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Sidewinder’s thinking is pretty clear: use their special antibodies and smart linker tech together to create ADCs that can take on tough cancers. They want to build therapies that make a real difference where it matters most.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Daniel Estes from Frazier Life Sciences praised the company’s pipeline. “Sidewinder’s bispecific ADCs have the potential to address key limitations in safety and efficacy for this class of therapeutics,” he said. This approach aims to target tumors more precisely and cut down on unwanted damage to healthy tissue. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company thinks that pairing bispecific targeting with site-specific conjugation really puts them ahead of standard ADCs. With this method, it&#8217;s easier to deliver the drug exactly where it’s needed, which helps patients do better and opens up more treatment possibilities.</span></p>
<h2><b>Scaling and Future Development<br />
</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_199709" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-199709" class="size-full wp-image-199709" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/create-a-futuristic-neon-lit-poster-elem_tO1gOvkRRRq9K-w9d3im3A_h1VmYtJ_Q-CDCI9U7Ub97Q_cover_hd.png" alt="Advanced ADC therapy targeting cancer cells with precision while minimizing impact on healthy tissue." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-199709" class="wp-caption-text">Sidewinder expands its ADC pipeline to develop safer, more precise cancer therapies using advanced antibody engineering. Source: Created by Ventureburn </p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Sidewinder’s new funding is set to drive a few key initiatives. They’re using the money to push their pipeline forward, beef up operations, and bring more talent on board so their preclinical and clinical programs move faster. They’re also sticking with their partners and doubling down on their tech platforms to broaden their portfolio.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Sidewinder popped up in 2023 with a pretty ambitious goal: change the way we treat cancer using advanced bispecific ADCs. They’re focusing on types of cancer that have always been tough to crack. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Their approach zooms in on receptor co-complexes — so their drugs head straight for the tumors, hitting them hard while sparing the rest of the body. That means fewer nasty side effects for patients.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The ADC field has really taken off lately, but safety, efficacy, and specificity are still big hurdles. Sidewinder thinks its approach can clear those obstacles.These obstacles with novel antibody engineering and advanced conjugation technologies.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/eclipse-ventures-1-3b/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Eclipse Ventures Secures $1.3B to Advance Physical AI Startups</span></a></p>
<h2><b>Investor Confidence and Industry Outlook</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Investors are clearly excited about Sidewinder and the future of next-gen ADCs. With Frazier Life Sciences and Novartis Venture Fund leading the latest funding round, there’s a lot of faith—not just in the tech itself, but in the team steering the ship.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Big names like OrbiMed, Goldman Sachs, and DCVC Bio have jumped in, which says a lot about the company’s momentum and promise. With new funding in hand, Sidewinder can push its research ahead, dive into preclinical studies, and start gearing up for clinical trials. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">They’ve also pulled together a board full of real experts—folks who actually get both the science and the business side. So, they’ve got a solid team backing them as they take the next steps. Bottom line: they want to stay sharp and move fast.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Right now, Sidewinder’s taking on some tough cancers: squamous cell carcinoma and colorectal cancer. Patients dealing with these don’t have a lot of great options yet. By targeting these diseases, Sidewinder’s aiming to actually change the game for people who really need better treatments.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To stay updated on crypto venture capital funding and market trends, visit our </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/category/news/venture-capital/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">venture capital news section</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> for more insights.</span></p>
