										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Physical AI: The Next Wave</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Eclipse Ventures just raised $1.3 billion, making it their biggest fundraising round ever. They split the money between a $591 million early-stage fund and a larger growth fund. With this haul, their total assets are nearing $10 billion.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Unlike most VC firms chasing software, Eclipse goes for physical AI—think artificial intelligence fused with </span><a href="https://www.mtu.edu/academics/robotics/what/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">robotics</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">, autonomous vehicles, and industrial hardware. They’re betting that the next big leap in tech won’t just happen on screens; it’ll show up in the real world. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Their portfolio backs that up: Wayve is working on autonomous vehicles, Redwood Materials does battery recycling, Arc builds electric boats, while Bedrock Robotics and Mind Robotics focus on construction robots and industrial AI.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Eclipse isn’t just handing out checks. They help these startups team up, share resources, tap into each other’s customer networks, and learn from one another’s operational know-how. The idea? Get companies from prototype to production way faster together than if they went it alone.</span></p>
<h2><b>Funding Supports Scale and Innovation</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Eclipse just landed $1.3 billion, and it’s pretty clear why. Physical AI is getting a lot of attention right now—hardware’s cheaper, machine learning keeps getting smarter, and everyone’s scrambling to fill jobs. Suddenly, robots and automation aren’t just cool tech—they’re actually practical. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Startups are under pressure to deliver solutions that work, not just in theory, but in the messy real world. Eclipse’s capital will fund investments across transportation, energy, infrastructure, compute, and defence. The firm also plans to incubate companies internally. By creating startups from scratch, Eclipse can shape product direction, assemble founding teams, and identify untapped opportunities in physical AI.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Partner Jiten Behl explains that Eclipse is focused on creating scale. Portfolio companies are encouraged to collaborate early, build proof points, and connect data across sectors. The goal is to generate an ecosystem where companies grow faster together. This venture firm’s got a strong hunch. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">They see the future of AI happening far away from cloud servers. Think robots on factory floors, automated vehicles on roads, and smart systems running machines. That kind of change doesn’t happen overnight, but with this big cash pile, Eclipse can jump into the biggest funding rounds, stay involved as these companies grow, and hold onto influence where it matters.</span></p>
<h2><b>Challenges and Opportunities<br />
</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_199688" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-199688" class="size-full wp-image-199688" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/a-futuristic-poster-showcases-a-dynamic-_zvILvlJXQBqRhTZroWou2A_JQyFzhcUT3motsGKc9-Gww.png" alt="Eclipse Ventures supports physical AI startups with funding, operational guidance, and manufacturing expertise in a competitive market." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-199688" class="wp-caption-text">Eclipse’s studio model helps physical AI startups navigate manufacturing, supply chains, and scaling challenges. Source: Created by Ventureburn</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Building physical AI startups isn’t easy. You have to handle supply chains, manufacturing, and those long development cycles—forget quick pivots, because iteration takes weeks or even months. The economics aren’t anything like digital products; everything hinges on the cost and logistics of real-world goods.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">That’s where Eclipse’s studio model comes in. Instead of just handing over funding, they incubate companies and bring serious operational expertise to the table. Startups get help with manufacturing, tap into customer networks, and lean on technical support. Mixing capital with hands-on guidance actually helps speed up getting products to market.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Honestly, competition keeps getting tougher in the physical AI space. Robotics funds, big company venture teams, and crossover investors all want a piece. Eclipse stands out because they don’t just invest—they build the companies from the ground up. Sure, that’s risky, but the payoff can be huge if things go well.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Regulation and economic shifts are also nudging investors toward physical AI. With geopolitical tensions, reshoring policies, and everyone obsessed with supply chain resilience, domestic manufacturing has climbed up the priority list. Startups pushing automation and advanced robotics are set to ride this wave — the macro environment is working in their favor.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/latent-raises-80m/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Latent Raises $80M to Expand AI Medication Access Platform</span></a></p>
<h2><b>Driving a Connected Ecosystem</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Eclipse wants to build a space where startups actually work together, not just side by side. When companies collaborate early on, they get their proof-of-concepts up and running faster and tap into a bigger pool of shared resources. It’s not just about pooling data and insights—they use what they learn from each other to run smoother and boost their edge in the industry.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Take autonomous vehicle software, industrial robotics, and energy storage, for instance. These companies can swap notes on AI models and workflows. That way, they can test ideas in the real world and make improvements quickly. The firm believes this integrated approach is critical for scaling physical AI technologies.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The capital will also fund internal incubations. Eclipse has already begun work on new startups across multiple sectors. The firm is targeting ideas that connect different industries and leverage cross-sector data. By doing so, they aim to build smarter AI models and accelerate adoption of physical AI solutions.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Eclipse’s $1.3 billion fund is not only a signal of confidence in the sector but a strategic bet. By combining traditional venture funding with a startup studio approach, the firm hopes to identify the best emerging companies and fill gaps where founding teams are lacking.</span></p>
